  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1658972054" />
    <a title="Anne Gazzolo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3066514-anne-gazzolo"><img alt="Anne Gazzolo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1370728331p2/3066514.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1658972054?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anne Gazzolo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anne Gazzolo" href="/user/show/3066514-anne-gazzolo">Anne Gazzolo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12966169-kingdom-of-summer">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1658972054" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13202123992141859430">I would have given this 5 stars if it had continued the format that made <i>Hawk of May</i> such a masterpiece: a powerful tale of Sir Gawain&apos;s life and struggles told by the man himself. This is told by his servant, Rhys, and dilutes a great deal of the power of the story that way, though I understand why the author did it, to show scenes that the warrior was not part of. Still I wish she had stuck to Gawain&apos;s POV. I would have loved it and him far more.</span>
  <span id="freeText13202123992141859430" style="display:none">I would have given this 5 stars if it had continued the format that made <i>Hawk of May</i> such a masterpiece: a powerful tale of Sir Gawain's life and struggles told by the man himself. This is told by his servant, Rhys, and dilutes a great deal of the power of the story that way, though I understand why the author did it, to show scenes that the warrior was not part of. Still I wish she had stuck to Gawain's POV. I would have loved it and him far more.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13202123992141859430" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


